    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-03-17T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-03-17T08:00:00-05:00" n="15"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d15">
                <head>15. Telegram From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RD3" type="from"
                        >Rusk</persName> to the <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d15fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 611.61/3–1762. Top Secret; <gloss target="#t_NIACT1">Niact</gloss>.
                        According to another copy, this telegram was drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>. (Ibid., Conference Files: Lot 65 D
                        533, CF 2060)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-03-17T14:00:00+01:00">March 17, 1962, 2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_SECTO1">Secto</gloss> 53. Eyes only for President and Acting
                    Secretary. Have had brief additional talks<note n="1" xml:id="d15fn1">The
                        additional talks have not been further identified.</note> with <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> alone in connection normal activities
                    conference and will be having bilateral dinner with him on Tuesday. Meanwhile,
                    members of his delegation have shown interest in exploring further with
                        <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_BCE2">Bohlen</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d15fn2">Regarding <persName corresp="#p_KFD1"
                            >Kohler</persName>’s conversation with <persName corresp="#p_SVS1"
                            >Semenov</persName>, see <ref target="#d14">Document 14</ref>. A
                        memorandum of <persName corresp="#p_BCE2">Bohlen</persName>’s conversation
                        with <persName corresp="#p_SVS1">Semenov</persName> on March 16 (<gloss
                            target="#t_SECDELMC1">SecDel MC</gloss>/29) is in Department of State,
                        Conference Files: Lot 65 D 533, CF 2074.</note> implications my presentation
                    “modus vivendi” approach last Tuesday. I am not taking initiative for full
                    exploration with <persName corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> over this week
                    end in order to give him chance to get Moscow reaction to what has been said
                    already. However, I expect to step up pace of private talks during coming week.
                    Senior member Soviet delegation expressed some concern to <persName
                        corresp="#p_TLET1">Thompson</persName> that I might be leaving next week end
                    because he said “Moscow moves very slowly”.<note n="3" xml:id="d15fn3">This
                        conversation has not been further identified.</note> I should like to leave
                    open exact date of my return because if we seem to <pb facs="0068" n="46"
                        xml:id="pg_46"/> be making any headway on Berlin, that should be overriding
                    claim on my time.</p>
                <p>[Here follow two paragraphs on disarmament.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
